<article id="post-3249" class="post-3249 post type-post status-publish format-standard hentry category-criminal-law category-human-rights contain has-byline">

	<div class="title">
					<h2 class="entry-title">Illegal Organ Trade in&nbsp;China</h2>				<div class="entry-byline">
			<span>Posted by <a href="http://hklawblog.com/author/yeungjck/" title="View all posts by Jacky Yeung">Jacky Yeung</a> on <a href="http://hklawblog.com/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/">October 3, 2014</a></span>
					</div>

		<div class="entry-meta">
						Posted in: <a href="http://hklawblog.com/category/criminal-law/" rel="category tag">Criminal Law</a>, <a href="http://hklawblog.com/category/human-rights/" rel="category tag">Human Rights</a>.			
			
							<span class="comments"><a href="http://hklawblog.com/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/#comments" title="Comment on Illegal Organ Trade in&nbsp;China">7 Comments</a></span>
					</div><!-- entry-meta -->

	</div><!-- end title -->

	<div class="entry-content">
		<p>By Lee Wing Yee, Ann</p>
<p><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-3250" src="http://hklawblog.files.wordpress.com/2014/10/illegal-organ-trade-in-china.jpg?w=627" alt=""   /></p>
<p>Picture reprieved from <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/may/27/kidney-trade-illegal-operations-who" rel="nofollow">http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/may/27/kidney-trade-illegal-operations-who</a></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Introduction</span></p>
<p>Organ trade is the trading activities involving inner human organs such as heart, liver, kidneys for organ transplantation. According to the ordinance of WHO, illegal organ trade occurs when organs are removed from the body for the purpose of commercial transaction. However, kidney sales are legal and regulated in Iran. In recent years, there is a dramatic rise in demand for organ donation over the world because of advanced medical technology. As there is only a few citizens agree to donate their organs after death, it widens the gap between demand and supply.</p>
<p><span id="more-3249"></span></p>
<p><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Current situation in China</span></p>
<p>From Chinese Law, it is illegal to buy or sell organs. However, in regard to the ‘’Rules Concerning the Utilization of Corpses or Organs for the Corpses of Executed Prisoners’’ adopted by China in 1984 , it provided that corpses or organs of executed prisoners could be harvested if no one claimed the body, if the executed prisoner volunteered to have his corpse so used, or if the family consented. A researcher for Human Rights Watch estimated that 90% of organs from China are from deceased prisoners. However, most of the harvested organs are sold to people from Hong Kong, Taiwan and Singapore. Moreover, according to Amnesty International researcher, Arlette Leduguie, Chinese citizens are executed for minimal reasons and that is a way of the government promoting the illegal human organ trade.It is one of the method for the corrupted Chinese government to earn more money and it becomes a highly lucrative industry.</p>
<p>On the other hand, organ trafficking in China remains widespread, especially for kidneys, are being sold online in many cities across the nations. Yet, the donors would receive for selling a kidney ranges from $800 to $160,000. Patients could have transplantation from corrupted doctors after transactions. Besides, poor workers sold their kidneys in order to pay debts as most of the people in China are under extreme poverty. It also raises the number of crime such as kidnapping children or even murdering another so as to earn profits.</p>
<p><span style="text-decoration:underline;">Debates about Legalizing Organ Trade</span></p>
<p>In my opinion, although legalizing organ trade can undoubtedly rescue more valuable lives, I still object to it. Firstly, I think it is unethical and immoral for donors to sell their organs for earning a relatively huge amount of money or for commercial use. For example, from a religious stance, selling a part of your body means selling your inner self and soul, as well as violating human dignity. Secondly, “Transplant Tourism’’ is becoming more popular in recent years. Safety problems may exist on both the donors and patients if the surgery and transplantation are done in other foreign countries or unauthorized hospitals. Therefore, there may be medical after-effects y but with no medical care afterwards. Lastly, it will indulge the black markets aboth thend increase the number of crimes which people may use illegitimate means to earn more profit from getting more organs such as murder.<br />
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Recommendation</span></p>
<p>I would like to share three suggestions. Firstly, I think donation is the most desirable means to obtain more organs from donors. Therefore, the Chinese government could start from educating children the virtue of helping other during lessons. Besides, encouraging altruistic organs especially kidney donation by doing more advertisement and talks. Secondly, the government should implement laws to prohibit black markets and frequent inspections are needed for the online trade. Penalty could be increased in order to raise awareness and frighten those middlemen. Lastly, it is to develop better system and regulation of organ donation. Donors would be rewarded such as health care vouchers instead of monetary transactions.<br />
<span style="text-decoration:underline;">Video Sharing:</span><br />
1. Organ Harvesting of Inmates in China Still Rife</p>
<p><span class='embed-youtube' style='text-align:center; display: block;'><iframe class='youtube-player' type='text/html' width='627' height='383' src='http://www.youtube.com/embed/U3_c3nnuiFQ?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;fs=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;wmode=transparent' frameborder='0' allowfullscreen='true'></iframe></span></p>
<p>Reprieved from <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U3_c3nnuiFQ" rel="nofollow">https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=U3_c3nnuiFQ</a></p>
<p>2. Organ trafficking: 6-year-old&#8217;s eyes stolen by organ traffickers in China</p>
<p><span class='embed-youtube' style='text-align:center; display: block;'><iframe class='youtube-player' type='text/html' width='627' height='383' src='http://www.youtube.com/embed/U3_c3nnuiFQ?version=3&#038;rel=1&#038;fs=1&#038;showsearch=0&#038;showinfo=1&#038;iv_load_policy=1&#038;wmode=transparent' frameborder='0' allowfullscreen='true'></iframe></span></p>
<p>Reference:</p>
<p>1. Action to stop thriving global organ trade must start at home. The Conversation. 2012, Jun 1. Retrieved from <a href="http://theconversation.com/action-to-stop-thriving-global-organ-trade-must-start-at-home-7333" rel="nofollow">http://theconversation.com/action-to-stop-thriving-global-organ-trade-must-start-at-home-7333</a><br />
2. China&#8217;s Human Organ Trade has a long history. Case Study 632. 2006, May 10. Reprieved from <a href="http://newsgroups.derkeiler.com/Archive/Soc/soc.culture.china/2006-05/msg00440.html" rel="nofollow">http://newsgroups.derkeiler.com/Archive/Soc/soc.culture.china/2006-05/msg00440.html</a><br />
3. Illegal organ trade thrives. 2012, Mar 27. South China Morning Post. Retrieved from <a href="http://www.scmp.com/article/996728/illegal-organ-trade-thrives" rel="nofollow">http://www.scmp.com/article/996728/illegal-organ-trade-thrives</a><br />
4. llegal Human Organ Trade from Executed Prisoners in China. 2012. Reprieved from <a href="http://sites.davidson.edu/anthro/global/2012/02/26/llegal-human-organ-trade-from-executed-prisoners-in-china/" rel="nofollow">http://sites.davidson.edu/anthro/global/2012/02/26/llegal-human-organ-trade-from-executed-prisoners-in-china/</a></p>
<p>5. Organ Trade. Wikipedia. Reprieved from <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organ_trade" rel="nofollow">http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Organ_trade</a></p>
