			<h2 id="comments-title">7 comments on &ldquo;<span>Illegal Organ Trade in&nbsp;China</span>&rdquo;</h2>

		<ol class="commentlist">
				<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-258000">
		<article id="comment-258000" class="contain">
			<footer class="comment-meta contain vcard">

				<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/808ca481439dd28a65ff472718b01cbd?s=40&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />
				<div class="comment-author">
				<span class="fn">Estelle (3035022722)</span> on <a href="http://hklawblog.com/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/comment-page-1/#comment-258000"><time pubdate datetime="2014-10-04T20:30:25+00:00">October 4, 2014 at 8:30 PM</time></a> said:
									</div><!-- .comment-author -->

				
			</footer><!-- .vcard -->

			<div class="comment-content"><p>In the past, I read some news about organ transplantation and illegal trade in China. Most of them are about living donors, such as healthy people died after donation and people sell them organs for profit. However, your article arose my interests in China’s executed prisoners organ donation, which is regarded as legal in China. </p>
<p>I am so surprised that more than 90% of transplanted organs are from executed prisoners’ body (Wang,hem organs for profit. However, your article arose my interests in China’s executed prisoners organ donation, which is regarded as legal in China. </p>
<p>I am so surprised that more than 90% of transplanted organs are from executed prisoners’ body (Wa 2013). Even though government states that every prisoner agrees to donate his organs or his family members consent to, I am still suspicious about their real willingness, because in China’s traditional perception, although people die, they should leave a complete body for their next generations. This is a basic respect of your body. And why does there exist a high chance that executed prisoners are willing to donate their body? In addition, a further concern arises. Now less and less people are sentenced to death in China recently and death sentence is likely to be abolished in the near future. What is worse, Chinese government also plans to cease using organs from executed prisoners (Li &amp; Blanchard, 2013). Consequently, this causes the continuous decrease of organ supply. While the demand remains stable or increase a lot, the price of per transplanted organ must rise sharply. Thus, under such situations, some people would like to donate their organs or perform illegal organ trade as driven by huge profits. So, in my opinion, it is quite hard for China to ban the illegal organ black market and living donation, as long as no alternative and effective voluntary organ donation systems appear. </p>
<p>Wang, Yaqiu. (July, 2013). China harvests the majority of its organs from executed prisoners. The Atlantic. Retrieved from <a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/china/archive/2013/07/china-harvests-the-majority-of-its-organs-from-executed-prisoners/277959/" rel="nofollow">http://www.theatlantic.com/china/archive/2013/07/china-harvests-the-majority-of-its-organs-from-executed-prisoners/277959/</a> on October 3, 2014</p>
<p>Li, Hui and Blanchard, Ben. (November, 2013). China to end use of prisoners&#8217; organs for transplants in mid-2014. The Reuters. Retrieved from <a href="http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/11/02/us-china-organs-idUSBRE9A011N20131102" rel="nofollow">http://www.reuters.com/article/2013/11/02/us-china-organs-idUSBRE9A011N20131102</a> on October 3, 2014</p>
</div>

