	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-258106">
		<article id="comment-258106" class="contain">
			<footer class="comment-meta contain vcard">

				<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/ac78b9e53d8070c8ff7a6f4314308fac?s=40&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />
				<div class="c58106" class="contain">
			<footer class="commeomment-author">
				<span class="fn">Si Hyun (Sean) Kim (2011550593)</span> on <a href="http://hklawblog.com/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/comment-page-1/#comment-258106"><time pubdate datetime="2014-10-05T00:39:35+00:00">October 5, 2014 at 12:39 AM</time></a> said:
									</div><!-- .comment-author -->

				
			</footer><!-- .vcard -->

			<div class="comment-content"><p>I would like to thank the author for this interesting post on organ trade. However, my viewpoints are different from the author’s; legalizing organ trade could provide more benefits than harms. Although like the author, people may object to organ trade based on three reasons: religious beliefs, safety issues, and increase in the number of crimes, the problem is that—religious-belief aside—murders to obtain organs, safety issues from “transplant tourism” to get organs already take place because there is always demand for such things. Thus, even if organ trade remains illegal, people with money will always try to look for ways to circumvent the law to obtain organs. In this aspect, legalizing organ trade may bring more benefits: more supply of organs, better regulation of organ trade, and more lives can be saved.<br />
1.	More supply: In the Philippines, organ sales are permitted, under the condition that the donor recipients are natives (Clark, “Selling”). As a result, the market is thriving with a reduced waiting list for organ transplants (Clark, “Selling”).<br />
2.	Better regulation: Bringing the organ trade market to the open will result in better regulation “since the stakes would be very high, market forces and social pressure would ensure that people are not intimidated or defrauded” (Gregory, “Why”).<br />
3.	Save lives: As a result of more supply, more lives can be saved.<br />
Illegalizing organ trade may not be the answer to organ trade because it flourishes black markets and most of the organ trafficking in the world already takes place in the underdeveloped countries (Gregory, “Why”). As Nadley Hakim, a transplant surgeon said, “this trade is going on anyway, why not have a controlled trade where if someone wants to donate a kidney for a particular price, that would be acceptable? If it is done safely, the donor will not suffer&#8221; (Gregory, “Why”).</p>
<p>Reference<br />
Clark, M., &amp; Clark, W. (n.d.). Selling Your Organs: Should it be Legal? Do You Own Yourself? Retrieved from <a href="http://www.forbes.com/sites/marciaclark/2013/06/13/selling-your-organs-should-it-be-legal-do-you-own-yourself/" rel="nofollow">http://www.forbes.com/sites/marciaclark/2013/06/13/selling-your-organs-should-it-be-legal-do-you-own-yourself/</a></p>
<p>Gregory, A. (2011, November 9). Why Legalizing Organ Sales Would Help to Save Lives, End Violence. Retrieved from <a href="http://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2011/11/why-legalizing-organ-sales-would-help-to-save-lives-end-violence/248114/" rel="nofollow">http://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2011/11/why-legalizing-organ-sales-would-help-to-save-lives-end-violence/248114/</a></p>
</div>

			<div class="reply contain">
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/?replytocom=258106#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm( "comment-258106", "258106", "respond", "3249" )' aria-label='Reply to Si Hyun (Sean) Kim (2011550593)'>Reply</a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->

	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-258944">
		<article id="comment-258944" class="contain">
			<footer class="comment-meta contain vcard">

				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/fceabb00318e92da499c87dcc6a8c635?s=40&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />
				<div class="comment-author">
				<span class="fn">Chan Lok Tung Dilys (3035109350)</span> on <a href="http://hklawblog.com/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/comment-page-1/#comment-258944"><time pubdate datetime="2014-10-06T13:57:22+00:00">October 6, 2014 at 1:57 PM</time></a> said:
									</div><!-- .comment-author -->

				
			</footer><!-- .vcard -->

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Thank you for raising the worth discussing subject regarding organ trade.  I think you have made a rather comprehensive analysis on the issue.</p>
<p>As you have mentioned, the illegal nature of organ trading has led to the emergence of black market, triggering series of unethical crimes such as murdering, corruption, kidnapping, organ trafficking and so on.  Safety is another problem as most illegal organ harvest occurs in unhygienic and poorly regulated places such as in unauthorised “hospitals” and without qualified doctors.  With a great many of negative consequences caused by illegal organ trading, I think there is a need to mitigate these problems.  </p>
<p>One way is to legalise organ trading.  More regulations can be set up by the Authority to make sure the procedures would meet safety standards.  More has to be done to investigate on ways to allow for a meaningful compensation for living and unrelated donors, without making the organ price unaffordable by patients.  Also, policies to reduce in breaching of ethical principles should be devised too.  </p>
<p>Another way is to encourage donations of organs after death.  Chinese people are still conservative in terms of believing that the whole body should be preserved as a respect to deceased persons.  Such belief obstructs the promotion of organ donation.  There are still few people willing to donate due to traditional thoughts, making it harder for patients to get organ transplant to extend their lives.  More education should stress on the charity nature of organ donating, on saving lives of the unfortunate.  </p>
<p>Reference:<br />
Peter, J. (2008). Legalizing the Organ Trade. TIME.</p>
<p><a href="http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1833858,00.html" rel="nofollow">http://content.time.com/time/world/article/0,8599,1833858,00.html</a></p>
</div>

			<div class="reply contain">
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/?replytocom=258944#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm( "comment-258944", "258944", "respond", "3249" )' aria-label='Reply to Chan Lok Tung Dilys (3035109350)'>Reply</a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->

	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment odd alt thread-odd thread-alt depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-259132">
		<article id="comment-259132" class="contain">
			<footer class="comment-meta contain vcard">

				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/9864fdc70af5781ef5a12297cd60942f?s=40&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />
				<div class="comment-author">
				<span class="fn">Ko Wai Ching Ann (3035068049)</span> on <a href="http://hklawblog.com/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/comment-page-1/#comment-259132"><time pubdate datetime="2014-10-06T21:46:58+00:00">October 6, 2014 at 9:46 PM</time></a> said:
									</div><!-- .comment-author -->

				
			</footer><!-- .vcard -->

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Thank you for your well-written post! The problem of organ trafficking in China is very serious as some enterprises provide money incentives for the poor in exchange of organs, and some may turn out to be murdered. In addition to encourage altruistic organ donation, I think the government should establish a standardized and ethical system of legal organ transplantation and fight against medical system based on “relationship”. For example, hospitals should follow the codes of conduct and uphold the ethic standards. Since organ trafficking requires doctors for transplant operation, it often involves a large amount of money for paying the illegal surgery as corruption. Therefore, the medical system should further increase transparency in order to deter backdoor policies and bribery from happening. Moreover, laws should be strengthened to against organ trafficking and to remove any loopholes. </p>
<p>Reference:<br />
1. Tazeen H. J., (2009). Organ Trafficking: Global Solutions for a Global Problem. American Journal of Kidney Diseases. Retrieved <a href="http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/716188" rel="nofollow">http://www.medscape.com/viewarticle/716188</a> </p>
<p>2. Fan J.Y. (2014). Can China Stop Organ Trafficking? The New Yorker. Retrieved </p>
<p><a href="http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/can-china-stop-organ-trafficking" rel="nofollow">http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/can-china-stop-organ-trafficking</a></p>
<p>3. Sheri R.G. (2012). Formula to Stop the Illegal Organ Trade:<br />
Presumed Consent Laws and Mandatory Reporting Requirements for Doctors. Retrieved <a href="http://www.wcl.american.edu/hrbrief/12/2glaser.pdf" rel="nofollow">http://www.wcl.american.edu/hrbrief/12/2glaser.pdf</a></p>
</div>

			<div class="reply contain">
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/?replytocom=259132#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm( "comment-259132", "259132", "respond", "3249" )' aria-label='Reply to Ko Wai Ching Ann (3035068049)'>Reply</a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->

	</li><!-- #comment-## -->
	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-259725">
		<article id="comment-259725" class="contain">
			<footer class="comment-meta contain vcard">

				<img alt='' src='http://2.gravatar.com/avatar/2f64c235cccdccd0d42f31cd06bd657a?s=40&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />
				<div class="comment-author">
				<span class="fn">Wong Zi Yan (3035105110)</span> on <a href="http://hklawblog.com/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/comment-page-1/#comment-259725"><time pubdate datetime="2014-10-07T19:33:47+00:00">October 7, 2014 at 7:33 PM</time></a> said:
									</div><!-- .comment-author -->

				
			</footer><!-- .vcard -->

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Thank you for raising the essential issue of organ trafficking in China. I am quite surprised that shadowy intermediaries selling of prisoners’ vital organs without their consent could have been a “billion-dollar business in China.” Bowing to international pressure over the past five years, the China’s Ministry of Health<br />
have recently made declarations and resolutions to reduce the number of executions and to curb organ tourism. </p>
<p>However, I doubt the effectiveness of the introduced measure as it was outlined only in the broadest of strokes, and the path to implementation is unclear. The Health Ministry’s plan to shift from prisoners’ organs to voluntary donations may reflect a political aspiration rather than an achievable goal. “They say they hope to stop executing prisoners in two years, but that is just a hope,” said Arthur Caplan, a professor of bioethics at N.Y.U. who has closely followed the organ trade in China. “I worry that they are not seriously committed to instituting cadaver donation,” which would diminish the need to harvest organs from prisoners (Fan, 2014). The existence of a flourishing underground organ trade in a country ruled by authoritarian decree rather than written law should not exactly come as a shock. Because the rules and decisions are made by the powerful and for the powerful, the average citizen has little incentive to respect the law. When it comes to health care, where the government has done little to provide a safety net for its citizens, they have all the more reason to take matters into their own hands. It remains to be seen whether such a system has any chance of combatting the entrenched corruption in managing organ transplantation, or whether it could be regulated so as to prevent the proliferation of a black market. </p>
<p>References:<br />
Campbell, D.; Davison, N. (May 27, 2012). Illegal kidney trade booms as new organ is &#8216;sold every hour&#8217;. The Guardian. Retrieved from: <a href="http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/may/27/kidney-trade-illegal-operations-who" rel="nofollow">http://www.theguardian.com/world/2012/may/27/kidney-trade-illegal-operations-who</a></p>
<p>Fan, J. (January 10, 2014). Can China stop organ trafficking?. The New Yorker. Retrieved from: <a href="http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/can-china-stop-organ-trafficking" rel="nofollow">http://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/can-china-stop-organ-trafficking</a></p>
</div>

			<div class="reply contain">
				<a class='comment-reply-link' href='/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/?replytocom=259725#respond' onclick='return addComment.moveForm( "comment-259725", "259725", "respond", "3249" )' aria-label='Reply to Wong Zi Yan (3035105110)'>Reply</a>			</div><!-- .reply -->
		</article><!-- #comment-## -->

