	<li class="comment even thread-even depth-1 highlander-comment" id="li-comment-259875">
		<article id="comment-259875" class="contain">
			<footer class="comment-meta contain vcard">

				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/ffc6c9851b9038f5a9833c44064342e0?s=40&#038;d=identicon&#038;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40' height='40' width='40' />
				<div class="comment-author">
				<span class="fn">AHN Do Hyun (2011541889)</span> on <a href="http://hklawblog.com/2014/10/03/illegal-organ-trade-in-china/comment-page-1/#comment-259875"><time pubdate datetime="2014-10-07T23:59:46+00:00">October 7, 2014 at 11:59 PM</time></a> said:
									</div><!-- .comment-author -->

				
			</footer><!-- .vcard -->

			<div class="comment-content"><p>Thank you very much for your detailed analysis of ongoing organ trade in China. In accordance to your opinion, I also object to the legalization of organ trade. While it is true that the organ demand is hitting the ceiling and legalizing such trade will save a lot more lives, it is still unethical to put a price tag on humans – something that conflicts with human rights. Without legalizing such trade, we can enhance the organ donation program to meet the demands of organs and preserve human dignity. For example, Spain adopted what is called “presumed consent” in 1990, and this has led doubling of organ donations in the country. Also, Creation of “Spanish National Transplant Organization” and “the introduction of a new organizational model around the process of deceased donation” have caused donation rate to increase dramatically. The centralized system analyzes every possible potential donor. In conclusion, there is always a way to meet the supplies of organs instead of setting a price on human body.</p>
<p>Reference</p>
<p><a href="http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(09)62141-3/fulltext" rel="nofollow">http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(09)62141-3/fulltext</a></p>
</div>

